<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n15032f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n15" href="#n15032f">N15 (VI.D.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n15all.htm#n15032f"> 32(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> grave rifling / for trove</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">As it now exists, the true beginning has disappeared. and its place has been taken by a purely fanciful account of Th&oacute;rir&apos;s adventures in Norway; in this the conventional method of <mark>obtaining treasure by digging into a grave-mound</mark> is slightly varied, as the buried berserk prevents Th&oacute;rir from carrying out his design, and directs him to a greater source of wealth. To obtain this, Th&oacute;rir and his comrades had to enter, at great risk, a cave inhabited by dragons, and were rewarded for their daring by abundance of gold, from which Th&oacute;rir derived his later distinctive epithet <small> W. A. Craige, <a name="ICEL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ICEL"><cite title="source">The Icelandic Sagas</cite></a>, (1913) 53-4</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c15208f" href="c15all.htm#c15208f">VI.C.15:208(f)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
